properties.Habitat: Coastal areas eucalypt forest and woodland
properties.Species_Profile: Acacia concurrens, commonly known as Black wattle or Curracabah, is a tall shrub endemic to eastern Australia, growing to a height of up to 10m. The botanic name concurrens describes the converging primary veins on the phyllodes (modified leaf stems which function as leaf). Bright yellow rod-shaped flowers are seen from late winter to early spring.
